<figureCitation box="[395,471,1336,1359]" captionStart="Figs 98" captionStartId="90.[163,203,1416,1438]" captionTargetBox="[165,1069,207,1390]" captionTargetId="figure-11@90.[165,1072,198,1399]" captionTargetPageId="90" captionText="Figs 98. Approximate distribution of species as noted." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5277677" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5277677/files/figure.png" pageId="47" pageNumber="1192">Fig. 98</figureCitation>
): This species is known from the 
<collectingCountry box="[812,877,1336,1358]" name="Brazil" pageId="47" pageNumber="1192">Brazil</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="47.[163,1068,1374,1425]" pageId="47" pageNumber="1192">
E t y m o l o g y: Thetrivialname, 
<emphasis box="[540,626,1374,1395]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="1192">petalosa</emphasis>
, is a Latin adjective that stems from 
<emphasis box="[995,1068,1374,1395]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="1192">petalus</emphasis>
(= broad), with reference to the comparatively broadened phallobasic lobes.
</paragraph>
